<div id="review_961319087" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/961319087" />
    <a title="Christopher" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/31555322-christopher"><img alt="Christopher" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1469165110p2/31555322.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/961319087?book_show_action=true">Jun 08, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Christopher" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Christopher" href="/user/show/31555322-christopher">Christopher</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780445043022" href="/book/show/570427.Midnight_Express">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31555322-christopher?shelf=biography">biography</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31555322-christopher?shelf=own-yes">own-yes</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31555322-christopher?shelf=read-yes">read-yes</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31555322-christopher?shelf=_reviewed">_reviewed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31555322-christopher?shelf=memoir">memoir</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31555322-christopher?shelf=biography-autobiography">biography-autobiography</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer961319087" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9794830592207949667">I read this for the first time when I was around 13, after my father began subscribing to a pay-TV network (ON-TV in L.A., for those in-the-know) and I started seeing R-rated movies for the first time. <i>Midnight Express</i> was one of the first R-rated movies I ever saw.<br/><br/>The film made a serious impression on me, since it was set in a strange country, in a prison which made American prisons look like country clubs. It depicted smuggling, torture, violence, squalor, tension, fear, depravity, drug use, m</span>
  <span id="freeText9794830592207949667" style="display:none">I read this for the first time when I was around 13, after my father began subscribing to a pay-TV network (ON-TV in L.A., for those in-the-know) and I started seeing R-rated movies for the first time. <i>Midnight Express</i> was one of the first R-rated movies I ever saw.<br /><br />The film made a serious impression on me, since it was set in a strange country, in a prison which made American prisons look like country clubs. It depicted smuggling, torture, violence, squalor, tension, fear, depravity, drug use, mental illness--all the fun stuff which fascinated an impressionable teenager like me.<br /><br />I found this book in our local bookstore after seeing the movie, and my father bought it, so I could relive the movie in book form. I read it several times--for a couple of years it was my favorite book, largely because it was so far removed from my comparatively comfortable childhood in California. Needless to say, it wasn't like one of those books about the sea which inspires a kid to join the merchant marine--rather, this was a cautionary tale which told me in no uncertain terms that I shouldn't be doing shit like this in real life--and I didn't.<br /><br />It's been many years since I last read it--I don't think I've read it since around 1980--but I still remember it well enough to know the differences from the movie. The most violent parts of the movie--biting off the nose of a hated fellow inmate; killing a corrupt guard on a clothes hook in self-defense--are not a part of Hayes' real-life story. His actual means of escape came not from a violent encounter, but from a very peaceful transfer to a low-security, island prison.<br /><br />I ought to read it again--some of the reviews here say it's not well-written, so I wonder how it plays to grown-ups.<br /><br />I thought it was interesting to read an article in recent years about how the movie version--the screenplay was by Oliver Stone--caused serious harm to Turkey's reputation around the world. Many tourists bought into the image of Turkey as a place of leering, slimy psychotics and stayed far away. And it was Billy Hayes, of all people, who has sought to help mend those wounds, as a sort of ambassador to the country where he was once incarcerated. It's a very interesting turn of events since <i>Midnight Express</i>.<br /><br />Billy Hayes wasn't--and perhaps still isn't--the kind of guy we'd like to be friends with, but he certainly had a great story to tell.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9794830592207949667" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

