<div id="review_864327455" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/864327455" />
    <a title="Susan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/28986032-susan"><img alt="Susan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1406761317p2/28986032.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/864327455?book_show_action=true">Feb 24, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Susan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Susan" href="/user/show/28986032-susan">Susan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer864327455" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7847015930739413355">This gut wrenching, brutality honest story of Billy Hayes a US citizen surviving a Turkish prison for a risky mistake of thinking he could take on a US plane several kilos of hashish was bold and outlandish. He is sent to a Turkish prison that is definitely not Club Med by any means and it is the beginning of sheer survival and endurance of staying alive after being sentenced to 33 years for his crime.<br/><br/>After numerous attempts from the US Consulate and his parents helping for his release he is sub</span>
  <span id="freeText7847015930739413355" style="display:none">This gut wrenching, brutality honest story of Billy Hayes a US citizen surviving a Turkish prison for a risky mistake of thinking he could take on a US plane several kilos of hashish was bold and outlandish. He is sent to a Turkish prison that is definitely not Club Med by any means and it is the beginning of sheer survival and endurance of staying alive after being sentenced to 33 years for his crime.<br /><br />After numerous attempts from the US Consulate and his parents helping for his release he is subjected to brutality and squalor conditions to where he basically goes insane. May it be divine intervention or a visit from his girlfriend at the prison with help from his family in US currency to manipulate or whatever he had to do to escape. Yes, did he escape. <br /><br />I found this autobiography brutally honest, unbelievable in the respect that someone could be subjected to such treatment and how Billy's resilience kept some part of hope alive to try and escape his sentence of not only for his crime but his emotional breakdown of his spirit. What he did was a daring act of courage and in some sense desperation to save his life from withering away. I love it and have read numerous of times and have seen the movie that gave you a true sense of the whole epic ordeal.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7847015930739413355" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


