  <span id="freeText17923223613655914584" style="display:none">The book is thrilling from the first page. Whether you eventually like Billy Hayes or not, he brings us through his experience in great detail and with real emotion. <br /><br />Though there is not a single redeemable Turk in the book that I can recall, and this is a problem, there are so many rich and varied characters throughout. I felt disappointed at times, as Billy did, when his friends were released from prison and thus from the narrative. <br /><br />There is also always a great sense of place - from the runway customs to the madhouse and the island prison, etc.<br /><br />It's also violent, but that shouldn't be surprising for a book about life inside a fascist prison.</span>
